Ranking — row-number, rank, dense-rank, and n-tile.

These are four ranking functions that run over a window. And the entire difference between them is how they handle ties. Picture three rows, where the first two are tied.

Row-number gives every row a unique, sequential number. Ties are broken arbitrarily. So the three rows get one, two, three.

Rank lets the tied rows share the same rank, and then the next rank skips ahead. So you get one, one, three.

Dense-rank also lets the tied rows share the rank, but it leaves no gap. So you get one, one, two.

And n-tile of n assigns each row to one of n quantile buckets.

The classic use case is top-n per group. You apply row-number over a window that partitions by the group and orders by the metric descending, and then you filter to the rows where the rank is less than or equal to n.
